instructions:
## Set up Algolia full-text search with Next.js

### 1. Install dependencies
- Install the Algolia JavaScript client and React InstantSearch:
  ```
  npm install algoliasearch react-instantsearch
  ```
- The `algoliasearch` package is the core client; `react-instantsearch` provides ready-made UI components.

### 2. Create an Algolia account and index
- Sign up at https://www.algolia.com and create a new application.
- Create an index (e.g., `products` or `articles`) â€” an index is a searchable collection of records.
- From the API Keys page, copy:
  - **Application ID** (`APP_ID`)
  - **Search-Only API Key** (public, safe to expose)
  - **Admin API Key** (private, server-only â€” used to write/update records)

### 3. Environment variables
- Add to `.env.local`:
  ```
  NEXT_PUBLIC_ALGOLIA_APP_ID=your-app-id
  NEXT_PUBLIC_ALGOLIA_SEARCH_KEY=your-search-only-api-key
  ALGOLIA_ADMIN_KEY=your-admin-api-key
  ```
- `NEXT_PUBLIC_` prefix makes the first two available in the browser.
- NEVER expose `ALGOLIA_ADMIN_KEY` to the client â€” it can mutate your index.

### 4. Create the Algolia client (`lib/algolia.ts`)
- Browser-side search client:
  ```ts
  import algoliasearch from 'algoliasearch/lite';

  export const searchClient = algoliasearch(
    process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_ALGOLIA_APP_ID!,
    process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_ALGOLIA_SEARCH_KEY!
  );
  ```
- Server-side admin client (for indexing):
  ```ts
  import algoliasearch from 'algoliasearch';

  export const adminClient = algoliasearch(
    process.env.NEXT_PUBLIC_ALGOLIA_APP_ID!,
    process.env.ALGOLIA_ADMIN_KEY!
  );
  ```
- Import `algoliasearch/lite` on the client for a smaller bundle; the full `algoliasearch` on the server.

### 5. Index your data (server-side)
- Create an indexing script or API route (`app/api/algolia/reindex/route.ts`):
  ```ts
  import { NextResponse } from 'next/server';
  import { adminClient } from '@/lib/algolia';

  export async function POST() {
    const index = adminClient.initIndex('products');

    // Fetch records from your database
    const products = await db.product.findMany();

    // Each record must have an `objectID` field
    const records = products.map((p) => ({
      objectID: p.id,
      name: p.name,
      description: p.description,
      category: p.category,
      price: p.price,
    }));

    await index.saveObjects(records);
    return NextResponse.json({ indexed: records.length });
  }
  ```
- `saveObjects` upserts records â€” safe to call repeatedly.
- Keep record payloads lean: only include fields you'll search or display.

### 6. Configure index settings
- Set searchable attributes and ranking in the Algolia dashboard or via code:
  ```ts
  await index.setSettings({
    searchableAttributes: ['name', 'description', 'category'],
    attributesForFaceting: ['category', 'filterOnly(price)'],
    customRanking: ['desc(updatedAt)'],
  });
  ```
- Do this once (e.g., in a setup script), not on every request.

### 7. Build the search UI
- Create a `SearchBox` component (`components/Search.tsx`):
  ```tsx
  'use client';

  import { InstantSearch, SearchBox, Hits, Highlight } from 'react-instantsearch';
  import { searchClient } from '@/lib/algolia';

  function Hit({ hit }: { hit: any }) {
    return (
      <div className="p-4 border rounded">
        <Highlight attribute="name" hit={hit} />
        <p className="text-sm text-gray-500">{hit.category}</p>
      </div>
    );
  }

  export function Search() {
    return (
      <InstantSearch searchClient={searchClient} indexName="products">
        <SearchBox placeholder="Search products..." className="w-full" />
        <Hits hitComponent={Hit} />
      </InstantSearch>
    );
  }
  ```
- `Highlight` wraps matched text in `<mark>` for visual emphasis.

### 8. Server-side search (for SEO and initial load)
- Use `getServerSideProps` or a Server Component to pre-populate results:
  ```ts
  import { adminClient } from '@/lib/algolia';

  export async function searchProducts(query: string) {
    const index = adminClient.initIndex('products');
    const { hits } = await index.search(query, { hitsPerPage: 20 });
    return hits;
  }
  ```
- Pass initial results to `InstantSearch` via the `initialUiState` prop to avoid a blank flash on load.

### 9. Autocomplete (optional)
- Install the autocomplete library:
  ```
  npm install @algolia/autocomplete-js @algolia/autocomplete-theme-classic
  ```
- Use `createAutocomplete` to build a custom dropdown for header search.
- Import the CSS: `import '@algolia/autocomplete-theme-classic/dist/theme.css'`.

### Common errors & fixes
- **`Index does not exist`** â†’ The index name in code doesn't match the one in Algolia dashboard. Names are case-sensitive.
- **Empty search results** â†’ Records haven't been indexed yet. Run your indexing script/endpoint.
- **`Invalid Application-ID or API key`** â†’ Wrong key or environment variables not loaded. Restart the dev server after editing `.env.local`.
- **Stale search results after DB update** â†’ You must re-index after mutations. Call `index.saveObjects` (upsert) or `index.deleteObject` in your mutation handlers.
- **`Cannot use import in server context`** â†’ You imported `algoliasearch/lite` on the server. Use the full `algoliasearch` package server-side.
- **Search triggers on every keystroke, causing rate limit** â†’ `react-instantsearch` debounces by default. If you use a custom input, debounce with 300â€“500ms.
- **Large bundle size** â†’ Always use `algoliasearch/lite` in client components, not the full client.

### What NOT to do
- Do NOT expose `ALGOLIA_ADMIN_KEY` as `NEXT_PUBLIC_`. Anyone with that key can delete or overwrite your entire index.
- Do NOT index sensitive user data (passwords, emails, payment info) â€” Algolia records are accessible via the search API.
- Do NOT store the full document in Algolia records. Store only searchable/displayable fields; keep the record size under 10 KB.
- Do NOT call `index.saveObjects` on every user request. Batch indexing in background jobs (e.g., Inngest) instead.
- Do NOT skip setting `searchableAttributes`. Without it, Algolia searches all attributes equally, which produces poor relevance.
- Do NOT use the Admin API Key in client-side code, even temporarily.
